WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:35.720 --> 00:37.240
Right, what have we got?

00:37.240 --> 00:38.800
I've narrowed it down to three.

00:38.800 --> 00:39.960
Nae repeats, mind.

00:39.960 --> 00:43.240
Naw, nae repeats. We're no' going up
the rubbish channels, either.

00:43.240 --> 00:46.480
BBC Nine and all that shite.
That's the wrong end of town.

00:46.480 --> 00:48.400
And I'm no' watching Gobblebox.

00:50.040 --> 00:51.680
Gogglebox?

00:51.680 --> 00:53.840
What did I say? Gobblebox.

00:53.840 --> 00:57.960
That would just be a pile of people
sitting round watching porno movies.

00:57.960 --> 00:58.960
Oh, aye, aye.

00:58.960 --> 01:03.480
Right, so the frontrunner is
A Mile In My Shoes, a doc.

01:03.480 --> 01:06.920
The trials and tribulations of two
men swapping their lives

01:06.920 --> 01:08.400
for a period of time.

01:08.400 --> 01:10.160
One's a chairman of a big company,

01:10.160 --> 01:12.600
and the other guy's a bampot.

01:12.600 --> 01:14.400
That sounds brutal.

01:14.400 --> 01:16.440
Socially experimenting on people.

01:16.440 --> 01:18.120
That's Mengele pish.

01:18.120 --> 01:19.320
Aye...

01:19.320 --> 01:21.880
Camera crew - "Right, come here,"
filming him.

01:21.880 --> 01:24.800
Boy's making an arse of it,
we're sitting at home heehawing

01:24.800 --> 01:26.600
and laughing at the poor bastard's
misery.

01:26.600 --> 01:28.680
It's definitely no' right.
It's bad form.

01:28.680 --> 01:31.920
Do you want to watch it?
Aye, get it on.

01:33.360 --> 01:37.280
Here, I wonder what would happen if
you and I swapped houses, Victor.

01:37.280 --> 01:40.080
Well, I'd come to you on a Tuesday
and you'd come to me on a Wednesday.

01:40.080 --> 01:42.080
Aye, as opposed to me coming to you
on a Tuesday

01:42.080 --> 01:44.600
and you coming to me on a Wednesday.
I would, however,

01:44.600 --> 01:48.560
be worried about my chip pan if you
were living in my house. How so?

01:48.560 --> 01:51.080
Well, I'd be lying in my bed -
actually your bed -

01:51.080 --> 01:52.920
eyes staring out my head,

01:52.920 --> 01:56.080
worried sick that you'd be rummaging
about in my kitchen,

01:56.080 --> 01:57.560
drunk on my drink,

01:57.560 --> 02:00.000
looking for things to deep-fry
in my chip pan.

02:00.000 --> 02:01.720
And why not? I'd be hungry.

02:01.720 --> 02:03.400
But I'd be bitterly disappointed

02:03.400 --> 02:06.520
because you've no' got anything in
your cupboards except tins.

02:06.520 --> 02:09.199
So then I'd be arseing about with
your shonky can-opener

02:09.199 --> 02:12.480
trying to wheedle the Spam out the
tin and into your fryer.

02:12.480 --> 02:14.400
There it is right there, Jack, eh?

02:14.400 --> 02:18.000
Frying Spam in the dead of night,
three sheets to the wind.

02:18.000 --> 02:19.560
"Oh, I know what I'll dae.

02:19.560 --> 02:21.760
"That Spam'll take
a wee while to cook through.

02:21.760 --> 02:25.040
"I'll just have a wee snooze on the
couch here cos I'm leathered."

02:25.040 --> 02:26.600
Oh, I know what this is.

02:26.600 --> 02:29.320
This is a chip-pan-fire scenario,
innit?

02:29.320 --> 02:32.080
Yes. First the handle -
puddle of black plastic.

02:32.080 --> 02:33.840
Then my curtains - boof!

02:33.840 --> 02:36.720
The whole kitchen ablaze.
The guy upstairs going off his nut,

02:36.720 --> 02:38.760
wondering where all the
heat's coming from!

02:38.760 --> 02:41.120
And me, at my age,
up umpteen floors

02:41.120 --> 02:42.640
on a fireman's ladder,

02:42.640 --> 02:44.480
trying to get out the building.

02:44.480 --> 02:46.360
That widnae bother me. How?

02:46.360 --> 02:47.960
Cos my worries would be over.

02:47.960 --> 02:49.720
I'd be burnt to crisp.

02:49.720 --> 02:51.360
Jack Black.

02:51.360 --> 02:53.480
Aye, lucky you, eh(?)

02:53.480 --> 02:55.440
Aye, well, that's a result.

02:55.440 --> 02:56.960
Oh! What?

02:56.960 --> 02:58.560
I've got chips on!

02:58.560 --> 03:01.040
HE CHUCKLES

03:06.200 --> 03:07.680
Enjoy your roll.

03:07.680 --> 03:10.240
Thanks, Sinead, hen.

03:10.240 --> 03:11.600
Oh!

03:13.400 --> 03:15.960
Please, Isa, join us(!)

03:15.960 --> 03:17.360
What can I get you?

03:17.360 --> 03:19.280
Oh, nothing for me.

03:19.280 --> 03:22.120
Just a tea, hen.
I'm watching my weight.

03:22.120 --> 03:24.800
I'll maybe have a wee roll
wi' sausage,

03:24.800 --> 03:28.760
and put an egg on it,
a wee bit of bacon.

03:28.760 --> 03:31.680
What's that you've got, Victor?
Roll and black pudding.

03:31.680 --> 03:33.840
Aye, a wee bit of black pudding
an' all, hen.

03:33.840 --> 03:35.800
Stick a tattie scone on the top
of it.

03:35.800 --> 03:38.200
Do you want beans an' all? Naw!

03:38.200 --> 03:39.960
SHE LAUGHS

03:39.960 --> 03:42.040
Well, maybe a wee forkful, hen.

03:42.040 --> 03:43.280
Right.

03:43.280 --> 03:47.360
Oh, uh, Sinead, congratulations on
your one-year anniversary.

03:47.360 --> 03:48.600
That's flew in.

03:48.600 --> 03:50.240
How did you know?

03:50.240 --> 03:52.320
I just seen wee Fergie
across the road.

03:52.320 --> 03:54.160
He was buying you something nice.

03:54.160 --> 03:56.360
Of course I'll no' say what it is.

03:56.360 --> 03:58.200
Flowers!

03:58.200 --> 03:59.880
That's remarkable, Isa.

03:59.880 --> 04:03.120
You manage to order the whole world
on a roll and keep a secret

04:03.120 --> 04:04.840
for 52 whole seconds.

04:04.840 --> 04:06.040
Shut up.

04:06.040 --> 04:07.840
A wee slice of tomato an' all, hen.

04:07.840 --> 04:10.520
Tomato. Can I get that to go?
Aye, nae bother.

04:10.520 --> 04:12.960
We've got a wheelbarrow
oot the back.

04:12.960 --> 04:14.240
Eh?

04:14.240 --> 04:15.440
Nothing.

04:15.440 --> 04:17.720
All right, team? Ah, Fergie.

04:17.720 --> 04:20.279
Happy anniversary, son. Flowers.

04:22.600 --> 04:24.360
All right, doll?

04:25.360 --> 04:26.960
Happy anniversary.

04:26.960 --> 04:29.600
Aw, they're lovely.
I got you some aftershave.

04:29.600 --> 04:32.200
What were you doing,
spending all that money?

04:32.200 --> 04:33.440
Calvin Klein?!

04:33.440 --> 04:35.080
No. It was only six quid.

04:35.080 --> 04:36.720
Calvin Klone.

04:36.720 --> 04:40.400
Thanks. Fire us up a roll
and scrambled egg, will you?

04:43.320 --> 04:45.360
SHE COUGHS

04:49.240 --> 04:51.480
Are you doing anything special
tonight?

04:51.480 --> 04:52.800
We're gonnae get a KFC.

04:52.800 --> 04:54.040
Fitting.

04:54.040 --> 04:57.800
I'm no' quite across what
all the anniversary years are.

04:57.800 --> 05:00.200
I know 50's golden and 40's ruby.

05:00.200 --> 05:02.440
So one year must be...chicken?

05:02.440 --> 05:05.880
No! Sure the first year's paper.

05:05.880 --> 05:08.040
Which a KFC is wrapped in.

05:08.040 --> 05:10.280
That was my thinking. Aye.

05:12.720 --> 05:15.640
Ohhh... What's the matter?
No...

05:15.640 --> 05:17.320
Nothing...

05:18.400 --> 05:20.040
Here you!

05:20.040 --> 05:21.920
That's enough of that. What?

05:21.920 --> 05:23.440
Looking at that lassie.

05:23.440 --> 05:25.080
What lassie?

05:25.080 --> 05:26.280
THAT lassie.

05:26.280 --> 05:27.840
What, her?

05:27.840 --> 05:30.840
That lassie that just came in there
in the two-piece suit

05:30.840 --> 05:34.960
and sat down at the window, with the
flattering light on her? Aye.

05:34.960 --> 05:36.680
I wisnae looking at her.

05:36.680 --> 05:37.840
You were.

05:37.840 --> 05:40.880
You're allowed to look, aren't you?
Fergie!

05:42.000 --> 05:45.240
Well, she's happy enough
wi' her flowers.

05:48.040 --> 05:49.720
Enjoy your roll.

05:51.720 --> 05:54.920
Isa, do you want
a hand out the door wi' that?

05:54.920 --> 05:57.440
Where did you get the flowers?

05:57.440 --> 05:58.720
Across the road.

05:58.720 --> 06:01.480
At least you didnae get them out the
garage, like a lazy bastard.

06:01.480 --> 06:03.920
I got them out the garage
across the road.

06:03.920 --> 06:05.400
You lazy bastard.

06:13.200 --> 06:14.960
Hi, Isa.

06:14.960 --> 06:16.440
Boabby, son.

06:16.440 --> 06:18.520
Wow, Navid. 40 year!

06:18.520 --> 06:21.360
Congratulations. That is some shift.

06:21.360 --> 06:24.800
Thank you, Boabby.
I thought, "How do you mark it?"

06:24.800 --> 06:26.440
You give something back.

06:26.440 --> 06:30.000
So I've rolled back the
prices to 1976.

06:30.000 --> 06:31.440
Excellent.

06:31.440 --> 06:34.560
I'll take two dozen bottles of
Scotch and all your fags.

06:34.560 --> 06:37.320
Scotch and smokes are exempt.
Why's that?

06:37.320 --> 06:39.800
Because I never had time to
phone Customs and Excise

06:39.800 --> 06:42.560
to inform them that some poxy shop
in Craiglang

06:42.560 --> 06:44.320
was having a rollback experience.

06:44.320 --> 06:45.680
Fair enough.

06:45.680 --> 06:47.840
A packet of Nic Naks, then.

06:47.840 --> 06:49.280
55 pence.

06:49.280 --> 06:51.280
They're always 55 pence.

06:51.280 --> 06:54.920
Where is my 1976 rollback?

06:54.920 --> 06:57.520
My shop opened in 1976.

06:57.520 --> 07:00.240
Nic Naks were launched in 1981.

07:00.240 --> 07:03.920
They are also exempt from the
rollback bonanza.

07:03.920 --> 07:05.720
Fine! A tube of Pringles.

07:05.720 --> 07:08.360
Pringles have been around
for donkey's.

07:08.360 --> 07:10.840
I'm afraid you are the donkey here,
Boabby.

07:10.840 --> 07:13.360
Pringles, the taste sensation,

07:13.360 --> 07:16.480
burst onto the snack scene in 1967.

07:16.480 --> 07:18.920
Good. Get them beeped.

07:18.920 --> 07:21.640
But that was in the US.

07:21.640 --> 07:26.520
In the UK, they were launched
in 1991. Exempt!

07:26.520 --> 07:29.040
Have you actually got anything
from 1976

07:29.040 --> 07:32.440
that costs what it cost in 1976,
Navid? Of course.

07:32.440 --> 07:35.400
This shop is a treasure trove
of savings today.

07:35.400 --> 07:38.080
You, uh, just need to find them.

07:38.080 --> 07:39.920
Da-dee!

07:44.480 --> 07:45.920
Warm.

07:45.920 --> 07:47.120
Warm.

07:47.120 --> 07:49.240
Hot. Hot. Roasting!

07:49.240 --> 07:50.360
Cold again.

07:58.960 --> 08:00.840
SHE MOUTHS

08:03.680 --> 08:05.960
Bleach?! You dick!

08:08.080 --> 08:09.600
Well done.

08:09.600 --> 08:13.240
Sale Of The Century.
The Price Is Right. Bleach!

08:13.240 --> 08:17.320
Okey dokey, then.
Today's price - 35 pence.

08:17.320 --> 08:20.920
1976 rollback bonanza price -

08:20.920 --> 08:22.600
34 pence.

08:22.600 --> 08:25.200
Ah! Nae luck, Boabby.

08:25.200 --> 08:27.080
Thanks for playing.

08:27.080 --> 08:29.080
Have you enjoyed your time with us?

08:29.080 --> 08:31.600
Aye, I've had a lovely...
Oh, for fu...

08:31.600 --> 08:34.840
Unbelievable! Bloody bleach.
I don't even need bleach.

08:34.840 --> 08:38.679
You don't need bleach? I've smelt
the toilets in the Clansman.

08:38.679 --> 08:40.679
SHE LAUGHS

08:40.679 --> 08:43.960
I'm a busy man, Navid.
I don't need this garbage.

08:43.960 --> 08:46.040
How are you busy?

08:47.560 --> 08:49.920
I've got the brewers
coming in the day.

08:49.920 --> 08:51.720
I've got barrels to change.

08:51.720 --> 08:54.360
I've got the cellar to clean.
I've got stocktake.

08:54.360 --> 08:58.480
It's all right for you, eh?
You've got it cushy.

08:58.480 --> 08:59.800
Cushy?

08:59.800 --> 09:02.360
You've got your missus doing all
your heavy lifting.

09:02.360 --> 09:05.120
You've got Isa cleaning the
place for you,

09:05.120 --> 09:08.680
sweating like Susan Boyle
in a cake shop,

09:08.680 --> 09:13.280
while you sit on your wee throne,
watching Loose Women.

09:15.320 --> 09:17.280
Cushy.

09:17.280 --> 09:20.720
Cheeky bastard.
There's nothing cushy about my job.

09:20.720 --> 09:23.800
TRANSLATION:

09:32.520 --> 09:35.800
Eric. Jack. Victor.

09:35.800 --> 09:37.000
Hi, Fergie.

09:37.000 --> 09:38.480
Have you got a minute?

09:38.480 --> 09:41.280
Lager, please, Boabby.
What do you want, Fergie?

09:41.280 --> 09:42.720
It's delicate.

09:42.720 --> 09:45.640
Uh-huh.
It's about...marriage and that,

09:45.640 --> 09:47.680
and I want to ask you guys advice.

09:47.680 --> 09:49.280
On marriage?

09:49.280 --> 09:52.400
No, no, you're talking to two old
fellas from a different era.

09:52.400 --> 09:54.840
I mean, I was married
at 21, for God's sake.

09:54.840 --> 09:57.280
An eejit! A young daftie.

09:57.280 --> 10:00.200
Aye, me an' all.
I don't know what I was thinking.

10:00.200 --> 10:03.160
21! Stupid, doolally bastard.

10:03.160 --> 10:05.120
I got married at 21.

10:05.120 --> 10:06.840
Did you, son? Carry on.

10:06.840 --> 10:09.000
I see yous two as the ancients.

10:09.000 --> 10:11.360
I'm no' sure I like that,
"ancients".

10:11.360 --> 10:14.240
No! The elder statesmen.
The wise men.

10:14.240 --> 10:15.320
Go on.

10:15.320 --> 10:16.720
It's just...

10:16.720 --> 10:18.240
See my marriage?

10:18.240 --> 10:21.440
I'm not saying it's no' good,
but a lot of time's passed.

10:21.440 --> 10:23.040
A year's a long time?

10:23.040 --> 10:24.640
Huh, right enough, aye.

10:24.640 --> 10:26.800
You must be sick of the sight
of one another.

10:26.800 --> 10:28.440
The old 12-month itch.

10:30.040 --> 10:32.080
Is this because you were ogling
at that lassie

10:32.080 --> 10:34.960
in the cafe the other day?
I've no' done nothing. Good.

10:34.960 --> 10:36.400
It's just...

10:36.400 --> 10:40.280
when I married Sinead, I hadn't
really been with anybody else.

10:40.280 --> 10:42.240
She's beautiful an' all that,

10:42.240 --> 10:44.520
I just feel I jumped in a bit quick.

10:44.520 --> 10:47.040
Right, let me stop you right there,
Fergie.

10:47.040 --> 10:50.280
Temptation is the trial of
every red-blooded man.

10:50.280 --> 10:53.360
Marriage is like
a fine old classic car.

10:53.360 --> 10:56.440
If you leave it lying,
well, it goes rusty.

10:56.440 --> 10:58.640
And then when you're
wanting inside it,

10:58.640 --> 11:01.480
you try to get your key in,
it'll no' start.

11:01.480 --> 11:04.520
You get me?
So, if you've got a classic car,

11:04.520 --> 11:07.800
make sure you're always
polishing the bonnet.

11:07.800 --> 11:09.520
I have been polishing the bonnet.

11:09.520 --> 11:11.440
Aye, but now you're wanting to

11:11.440 --> 11:13.840
polish this other lassie's
headlights. Eh?

11:13.840 --> 11:16.680
You see, Fergie, your modern women
have all these new needs.

11:16.680 --> 11:18.760
You know, fresh demands.

11:18.760 --> 11:20.480
Like the cly-toris.

11:20.480 --> 11:23.280
Don't get embarrassed, Fergie.
Victor's right.

11:23.280 --> 11:25.040
Today, it's all about the
cly-torises

11:25.040 --> 11:27.880
and making a real effort to reach
your woman's G Plan.

11:27.880 --> 11:29.240
G-spot, Jack.

11:29.240 --> 11:30.760
G-spot? What did I say?

11:30.760 --> 11:32.680
G Plan. That's furniture.

11:32.680 --> 11:34.280
Oh, aye.

11:34.280 --> 11:37.160
So, when you have located
the G-spot...

11:37.160 --> 11:39.400
Listen, guys, that'll dae me.

11:39.400 --> 11:40.960
That's plenty.

11:40.960 --> 11:43.520
No, give us a minute,
we know what we're talking about.

11:43.520 --> 11:46.520
You've seen Kayleigh.
She's beautiful, man.

11:46.520 --> 11:48.400
What would you dae?

11:48.400 --> 11:50.760
I'll tell you what I'd dae.
Carpe diem.

11:50.760 --> 11:52.240
Carpe diem?

11:52.240 --> 11:54.360
Carpe diem, Fergie.

11:54.360 --> 11:55.840
Carpe diem...

11:59.120 --> 12:00.440
Carpe diem.

12:02.520 --> 12:04.680
Two lager, Boabby.

12:04.680 --> 12:07.080
What does "carpe diem" mean, Jack?

12:07.080 --> 12:08.800
Carpe diem? It's Latin, sure.

12:08.800 --> 12:10.920
It means do right thing.
Toe the line.

12:10.920 --> 12:12.560
Behave yourself.

12:12.560 --> 12:14.320
Oh, aye, stick with the missus.

12:14.320 --> 12:16.240
Straighten up and fly right!

12:16.240 --> 12:17.960
Carpe diem!

12:17.960 --> 12:22.640
Have you got 50 pence
for a cup of tea, mate? No?

12:22.640 --> 12:24.280
Mick?

12:24.280 --> 12:26.880
Aw, Fergie, it's yourself.

12:26.880 --> 12:31.640
Aye. Here, Mick, you're good wi'
words and that, aren't you?

12:31.640 --> 12:35.080
It has been suggested that my
loquaciousness is legendary.

12:35.080 --> 12:38.680
Aye, well, have you heard the
phrase...

12:41.040 --> 12:43.000
"...carpe diem"?

12:43.000 --> 12:44.840
Yes. What about it?

12:44.840 --> 12:46.240
What does it mean?

12:46.240 --> 12:47.800
It's a Latin aphorism,

12:47.800 --> 12:52.720
taken from book one of the Roman
poet Horace's work Odes from 23 BC,

12:52.720 --> 12:54.880
which I don't hold with.

12:54.880 --> 12:56.840
I reckon it's later.

12:56.840 --> 12:58.560
Aye, later.

12:58.560 --> 13:00.320
But what does it mean?

13:00.320 --> 13:04.560
Seize the day, as in now,
get it done.

13:04.560 --> 13:07.600
Don't leave it hinging
till it gets minging.

13:07.600 --> 13:09.800
Seize the day?!

13:10.920 --> 13:13.400
Wow. Thanks, Jack.

13:13.400 --> 13:15.720
Thanks, Victor.

13:15.720 --> 13:17.400
Seize the day.

13:17.400 --> 13:19.320
Here I come, seize the day.

13:22.520 --> 13:24.400
Navid? What can I get you?

13:24.400 --> 13:27.920
You can get me an apology.
Make it a large one!

13:27.920 --> 13:30.240
Apologise? For what?

13:30.240 --> 13:33.440
All that cushy crack in the shop.
What about it?

13:33.440 --> 13:37.760
Let me take you back 40 years to
when I started my cushy wee shop.

13:37.760 --> 13:41.440
I was the only dark face in
all of Craiglang.

13:41.440 --> 13:45.480
Every time I put my shutters up,
somebody put my windows in.

13:45.480 --> 13:49.560
Every time I shut my shop at night,
somebody broke in.

13:49.560 --> 13:51.720
Chucking out alcoholics,

13:51.720 --> 13:54.160
patting down shoplifters,

13:54.160 --> 13:56.000
battling neds,

13:56.000 --> 13:58.520
dodging boys with blades.

13:58.520 --> 14:00.360
It was a war zone.

14:00.360 --> 14:03.440
And meanwhile,
what were you doing, eh?

14:03.440 --> 14:07.880
"Oh, would you like a piece of ice
in your Campari and soda?"

14:07.880 --> 14:11.240
"Oh, salted or dry roasted?"

14:11.240 --> 14:13.200
So what are you getting at?

14:13.200 --> 14:15.240
I'll tell you what I'm getting at.

14:15.240 --> 14:18.400
I could do your job
standing on my head.

14:18.400 --> 14:20.880
But you widnae last ten minutes
in my place.

14:20.880 --> 14:24.160
So apologise,
or walk a mile in my shoes.

14:26.280 --> 14:27.680
Thing is, Navid,

14:27.680 --> 14:30.760
sometimes I just open my mouth
and I let my belly rumble.

14:30.760 --> 14:34.400
I've upset you and, for that,
I'm sorry.

14:34.400 --> 14:36.000
Well, good.

14:37.400 --> 14:39.280
I accept.

14:39.280 --> 14:44.040
So you away back to your cushy
wee sweetie shop!

14:44.040 --> 14:46.240
Bastard! Oh, Jesus!

